{{wikipedia}}
==English==
===Etymology===
From Greek [[ίσος]] ([[iso-]], "equal", "same") + [[τόπος]] ("place"), because the different isotopes of a chemical element always occupy the same position in the [[periodic table]] of elements.

===Noun===
'''isotope''' (''plural:'' '''isotopes''')

#{{physics}} Any of two or more [[atom]]s of an [[element]] having the same number of [[proton]]s, but a different number of [[neutron]]s in its [[nucleus]]. As a [[consequence]], it will have the same [[atomic number]] but a different [[mass number]] ([[atomic weight]]).

